# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: model-quantization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The **bfloat16** (**brain floating point**) floating-point format is a computer number format occupying 16 bits in computer memory; it represents a wide dynamic range of numeric values by using a floating radix point.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] This format is a shortened (16-bit) version of the 32-bit IEEE 754 single-precision floating-point format (binary32) with the intent of accelerating machine learning and near-sensor computing.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] It preserves the approximate dynamic range of 32-bit floating-point numbers by retaining 8 exponent bits, but supports only an 8-bit precision rather than the 24-bit significand of the binary32 format.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] More so than single-precision 32-bit floating-point numbers, bfloat16 numbers are unsuitable for integer calculations, but this is not their intended use.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Bfloat16 is used to reduce the storage requirements and increase the calculation speed of machine learning algorithms.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The bfloat16 format was developed by Google Brain, an artificial intelligence research group at Google, for use in its TPU v2, released in 2017.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Many libraries support bfloat16, such as CUDA, Intel oneAPI Math Kernel Library, AMD ROCm, AMD Optimizing CPU Libraries, PyTorch, and TensorFlow.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] On these platforms, bfloat16 may also be used in mixed-precision arithmetic, where bfloat16 numbers may be operated on and expanded to wider data types.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Preserving the exponent bits maintains the 32-bit float's range of ≈ 10−38 to ≈ 3 × 1038.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The bfloat16 binary floating-point exponent is encoded using an offset-binary representation, with the zero offset being 127; also known as exponent bias in the IEEE 754 standard.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Thus, in order to get the true exponent as defined by the offset-binary representation, the offset of 127 has to be subtracted from the value of the exponent field.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The minimum and maximum values of the exponent field (00H and FFH) are interpreted specially, like in the IEEE 754 standard formats.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The most common use case is the conversion between IEEE 754 binary32 and bfloat16.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The following section describes the conversion process and its rounding scheme in the conversion.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Note that there are other possible scenarios of format conversions to or from bfloat16.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Just as in IEEE 754, positive and negative infinity are represented with their corresponding sign bits, all 8 exponent bits set (FFhex) and all significand bits zero.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Just as in IEEE 754, NaN values are represented with either sign bit, all 8 exponent bits set (FFhex) and not all significand bits zero.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] where at least one of *k, l, m, n, o, p,* or *q* is 1.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] As with IEEE 754, NaN values can be quiet or signaling, although there are no known uses of signaling bfloat16 NaNs.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] Bfloat16 is designed to maintain the number range from the 32-bit IEEE 754 single-precision floating-point format (binary32), while reducing the precision from 24 bits to 8 bits.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] This means that the precision is between two and three decimal digits, and bfloat16 can represent finite values up to about 3.4 × 1038.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] These examples are given in bit *representation*, in hexadecimal and binary, of the floating-point value.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] This includes the sign, (biased) exponent, and significand.
[src:model-quantization/bfloat16-floating-point-format] The maximum positive finite value of a normal bfloat16 number is 3.38953139 × 1038, slightly below (224 − 1) × 2−23 × 2127 = 3.402823466 × 1038, the max finite positive value representable in single precision.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In computing, **fixed-point** is a method of representing fractional (non-integer) numbers by storing a fixed number of digits of their fractional part.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Dollar amounts, for example, are often stored with exactly two fractional digits, representing the cents (1/100 of a dollar).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] More generally, the term may refer to representing fractional values as integer multiples of some fixed small unit, e.g., a fractional amount of hours as an integer multiple of ten-minute intervals.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Fixed-point number representation is often contrasted to the more complicated and computationally demanding floating-point representation.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In the fixed-point representation, the fraction is often expressed in the same number base as the integer part, but using negative powers of the base *b*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The most common variants are decimal (base 10) and binary (base 2).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The latter is commonly known also as **binary scaling**.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Thus, if *n* fraction digits are stored, the value will always be an integer multiple of *b*−*n*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Fixed-point representation can also be used to omit the low-order digits of integer values, for instance, when representing large dollar values as multiples of $1000 ($1K).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] When decimal fixed-point numbers are displayed for human reading, the fraction digits are usually separated from those of the integer part by a radix character (usually "." in English, but "," or some other symbol in many other languages).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Internally, however, there is no separation, and the distinction between the two groups of digits is defined only by the programs that handle such numbers.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Fixed-point representation was the norm in mechanical calculators.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Fixed-point representation is still the norm for field-programmable gate array (FPGA) implementations, as floating-point support in an FPGA requires significantly more resources than fixed-point support.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] A fixed-point representation of a fractional number is essentially an integer that is to be implicitly multiplied by a fixed scaling factor.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] For example, the value 1.23 can be stored in a variable as the integer value 123 with an implicit scaling factor of 1/100.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This representation allows standard integer arithmetic logic units to perform rational number calculations.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Negative values are usually represented in binary fixed-point formats as a signed integer in two's complement representation with an implicit scaling factor as above.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The sign of the value will always be indicated by the most significant bit (1 = negative, 0 = non-negative), even if the number of fraction bits is greater than or equal to the total number of bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Alternatively, negative values can be represented by an integer in the sign-magnitude format, in which case the sign is never included in the number of implied fraction bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This variant is more commonly used in decimal fixed-point arithmetic.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] A program will usually assume that all fixed-point values that will be stored into a given variable, or will be produced by a given instruction, will have the same scaling factor.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This parameter can usually be chosen by the programmer depending on the precision needed and the range of values to be stored.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The scaling factor of a variable or formula may not appear explicitly in the program.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Coding best practices then requires that it be provided in the documentation, at least as a comment in the source code.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] For greater efficiency, scaling factors are often chosen to be powers (positive or negative) of the base *b* used to represent the integers internally.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] However, often the best scaling factor is dictated by the application.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Thus, one often uses scaling factors that are powers of 10 (e.g., 1/100 for dollar values) for human convenience, even when the integers are represented internally in binary.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Decimal scaling factors also mesh well with the metric (SI) system, since the choice of the fixed-point scaling factor is often equivalent to the choice of a unit of measure (like centimeter or micron in relation to meter).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] However, other scaling factors may be used occasionally, e.g., a fractional amount of hours may be represented as an integer number of seconds; that is, as a fixed-point number with a scale factor of 1/3600.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Even with the most careful rounding, fixed-point values represented with a scaling factor *S* may have an error of up to ±0.5 × *S* in the stored integer value.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Therefore, smaller scaling factors generally produce more accurate results.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] On the other hand, a smaller scaling factor means a smaller range of the values that can be stored in a given program variable.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The maximum fixed-point value that can be stored into a variable is the largest integer value that can be stored into it, multiplied by the scaling factor, and similarly for the minimum value.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] For example, the table below gives the implied scaling factor *S*, the minimum and maximum representable values *V*min and *V*max, and the accuracy *δ* = *S*/2 of values that could be represented in 16-bit signed binary fixed point format, depending on the number *f* of implied fraction bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Fixed-point formats with scaling factors of the form 2*n*−1 (namely 1, 3, 7, 15, 31, etc.) have been said to be appropriate for image processing and other digital signal processing tasks.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] They provide more consistent conversions between fixed- and floating-point values than 2*n* scaling.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The Julia programming language implements both versions.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Any binary fraction *a*/2*m*, such as 1/16 or 17/32, can be exactly represented in fixed-point, with a power-of-two scaling factor 1/2*n* with any *n* ≥ *m*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] However, most decimal fractions like 0.1 or 0.123 are infinite repeating fractions in base 2, and hence cannot be represented that way.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Similarly, any decimal fraction *a*/10*m*, such as 1/100 or 37/1000, can be exactly represented in fixed point with a power-of-ten scaling factor 1/10*n* with any *n* ≥ *m*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] More generally, a rational number *a*/*b*, with *a* and *b* relatively prime and *b* positive, can be exactly represented in binary fixed point only if *b* is a power of 2; and in decimal fixed point only if *b* has no prime factors other than 2 or 5.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Fixed-point computations can be faster or use less hardware than floating-point ones.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If the range of the values to be represented is known in advance and is sufficiently limited, fixed point can make better use of the available bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] For a digital audio recording requiring less than 40 dB of headroom, a 32-bit fixed-point has a higher signal-to-noise ratio than floating-point.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Programs using fixed-point computations are usually more portable than those using floating-point since they do not depend on the availability of an FPU.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This advantage was particularly strong before the IEEE Floating Point Standard was widely adopted, when floating-point computations with the same data would yield different results depending on the manufacturer, and often on the computer model.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Many embedded processors lack an FPU, because integer arithmetic units require substantially fewer logic gates and consume much smaller chip area than an FPU; and software emulation of floating-point on low-speed devices would be too slow for most applications.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] CPU chips for the earlier personal computers and game consoles, like the Intel 386 and 486SX, also lacked an FPU.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The *absolute* resolution (difference between successive values) of any fixed-point format is constant over the whole range, namely the scaling factor *S*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In contrast, the *relative* resolution of a floating-point format is approximately constant over its whole range, varying within a factor of the base *b*; whereas their *absolute* resolution varies by many orders of magnitude, like the values themselves.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In many cases, the rounding and truncation errors of fixed-point computations are easier to analyze than those of the equivalent floating-point computations.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Applying linearization techniques to truncation, such as dithering and/or noise shaping is more straightforward within fixed-point arithmetic.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] On the other hand, the use of fixed point requires greater care by the programmer.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Avoidance of overflow requires much tighter estimates for the ranges of variables and all intermediate values in the computation, and often also extra code to adjust their scaling factors.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Fixed-point programming normally requires the use of integer types of different widths.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Fixed-point applications can make use of block floating point, which is a fixed-point environment having each array (block) of fixed-point data be scaled with a common exponent in a single word.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] A common use of decimal fixed-point is for storing monetary values, for which the complicated rounding rules of floating-point numbers are often a liability.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] For example, the open-source money management application GnuCash, written in C, switched from floating-point to fixed-point as of version 1.6, for this reason.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Binary fixed-point (binary scaling) was widely used from the late 1960s to the 1980s for real-time computing that was mathematically intensive, such as flight simulation and in nuclear power plant control algorithms.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] It is still used in many DSP applications and custom-made microprocessors.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Computations involving angles would use binary angular measurement.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Binary fixed point is used in the STM32G4 series CORDIC co-processors and in the discrete cosine transform algorithms used to compress JPEG images.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Electronic instruments such as electricity meters and digital clocks often use polynomials to compensate for introduced errors, e.g. from temperature or power supply voltage.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The coefficients are produced by polynomial regression.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Binary fixed-point polynomials can utilize more bits of precision than floating-point and do so in fast code using inexpensive CPUs.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Accuracy, crucial for instruments, compares well to equivalent-bit floating-point calculations, if the fixed-point polynomials are evaluated using Horner's method (e.g.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] *y* = ((*ax* + *b*)*x* + *c*)*x* + *d*) to reduce the number of times that rounding occurs, and the fixed-point multiplications utilize rounding addends.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] To add or subtract two values with the same implicit scaling factor, it is sufficient to add or subtract the underlying integers; the result will have their common implicit scaling factor and can thus be stored in the same program variables as the operands.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] These operations yield the exact mathematical result, as long as no overflow occurs—that is, as long as the resulting integer can be stored in the receiving program variable.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If overflow happens, it occurs like with ordinary integers of the same signedness.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In the unsigned and signed-via-two's-complement cases, the overflow behaviour is well-known as a finite group.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If the operands have different scaling factors, then they must be converted to a common scaling factor before the operation.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] To multiply two fixed-point numbers, it suffices to multiply the two underlying integers and assume that the scaling factor of the result is the product of their scaling factors.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The result will be exact, with no rounding, provided that it does not overflow the receiving variable.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In binary, it is common to use a scaling factor that is a power of two.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] After the multiplication, the scaling factor can be divided away by shifting right.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Shifting is simple and fast in most computers.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] When right-shifting or a typical integer-division instruction (such as C integer division and x86 idiv) is used, the result is equivalent to a flooring division (floor(x/y)).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] A method with rounding can be used to reduce the error introduced.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] These rounding methods are usable in any scaling through integer division.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] For example, they are also applicable to the discussion on rescaling.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The division of fixed-point numbers can be understood as the division of two fractions of potentially different denominators (scaling factors).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] With very similar s and q, the above algorithm results in an overly coarse scaling factor.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This can be improved by first converting the dividend to a smaller scaling factor.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] A different way to think about the scaling is to consider division, the inverse operation of multiplication.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If multiplication leads to a finer scaling factor, it is reasonable that the dividend needs to have a finer scaling factor as well to recover the original value given.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In fixed-point computing, it is often necessary to convert a value to a different scaling factor.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] To convert a number from a fixed point type with scaling factor *R* to another type with scaling factor *S*, the underlying integer must be multiplied by the ratio *R*/*S*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If the scaling factor is a power of the base used internally to represent the integer, changing the scaling factor requires only dropping low-order digits of the integer, or appending zero digits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] However, this operation must preserve the sign of the number.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In two's complement representation, that means extending the sign bit as in arithmetic shift operations.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If *S* does not divide *R* (in particular, if the new scaling factor *S* is greater than the original *R*), the new integer may have to be rounded.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In particular, if *r* and *s* are fixed-point variables with implicit scaling factors *R* and *S*, the operation *r* ← *r*×*s* requires multiplying the respective integers and explicitly dividing the result by *S*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The result may have to be rounded, and overflow may occur.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] For example, if the common scaling factor is 1/100, multiplying 1.23 by 0.25 entails multiplying 123 by 25 to yield 3075 with an intermediate scaling factor of 1/10000.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In order to return to the original scaling factor 1/100, the integer 3075 then must be multiplied by 1/100, that is, divided by 100, to yield either 31 (0.31) or 30 (0.30), depending on the rounding policy used.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Similarly, the operation *r* ← *r*/*s* will require dividing the integers and explicitly multiplying the quotient by *S*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Rounding and/or overflow may occur here too.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] To convert a number from floating point to fixed point, one may multiply it by the scaling factor *S*, then round the result to the nearest integer.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Care must be taken to ensure that the result fits in the destination variable or register.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Depending on the scaling factor and storage size, and on the range input numbers, the conversion may not entail any rounding.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] To convert a fixed-point number to floating-point, one may convert the integer to floating-point and then divide it by the scaling factor *S*.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This conversion may entail rounding if the integer's absolute value is greater than 224 (for binary single-precision IEEE floating point) or of 253 (for double-precision).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Overflow or underflow may occur if |*S*| is *very* large or *very* small, respectively.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Typical processors do not have specific support for fixed-point arithmetic.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] However, most computers with binary arithmetic have fast bit shift instructions that can multiply or divide an integer by any power of 2; in particular, an arithmetic shift instruction.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] These instructions can be used to quickly change scaling factors that are powers of 2, while preserving the sign of the number.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Early computers like the IBM 1620 and the Burroughs B3500 used a binary-coded decimal (BCD) representation for integers, namely base 10 where each decimal digit was independently encoded with 4 bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Some processors, such as microcontrollers, may still use it.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In such machines, conversion of decimal scaling factors can be performed by bit shifts and/or by memory address manipulation.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Some DSP architectures offer native support for specific fixed-point formats, for example, signed *n*-bit numbers with *n*−1 fraction bits (whose values may range between −1 and almost +1).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The support may include a multiply instruction that includes renormalization—the scaling conversion of the product from 2*n*−2 to *n*−1 fraction bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If the CPU does not provide that feature, the programmer must save the product in a large enough register or temporary variable, and code the renormalization explicitly.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Overflow happens when the result of an arithmetic operation is too large to be stored in the designated destination area.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In addition and subtraction, the result may require one bit more than the operands.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In multiplication of two unsigned integers with *m* and *n* bits, the result may have *m*+*n* bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In case of overflow, the high-order bits are usually lost, as the un-scaled integer gets reduced modulo 2*n* where *n* is the size of the storage area.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The sign bit, in particular, is lost, which may radically change the sign and the magnitude of the value.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Some processors can set a hardware overflow flag and/or generate an exception on the occurrence of an overflow.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Some processors may instead provide saturation arithmetic: if the result of an addition or subtraction were to overflow, they store instead the value with the largest magnitude that can fit in the receiving area and has the correct sign.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] However, these features are not very useful in practice; it is generally easier and safer to select scaling factors and word sizes so as to exclude the possibility of overflow, or to check the operands for excessive values before executing the operation.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Explicit support for fixed-point numbers is provided by a few programming languages, notably PL/I, COBOL, Ada, JOVIAL, and Coral 66.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] They provide fixed-point data types, with a binary or decimal scaling factor.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The compiler automatically generates code to do the appropriate scaling conversions when doing operations on these data types, when reading or writing variables, or when converting the values to other data types, such as floating-point.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Most of those languages were designed between 1955 and 1990.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] More modern languages usually do not offer any fixed-point data types or support for scaling factor conversion.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] That is also the case for several older languages that are still very popular, like FORTRAN, C and C++.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The wide availability of fast floating-point processors, with strictly standardized behavior, has greatly reduced the demand for binary fixed-point support.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Similarly, the support for decimal floating point in some programming languages, like C# and Python, has removed most of the need for decimal fixed-point support.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In the few situations that call for fixed-point operations, they can be implemented by the programmer, with explicit scaling conversion, in any programming language that supports explicit integer types.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] On the other hand, all relational databases and the SQL notation support fixed-point decimal arithmetic and storage of numbers.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] PostgreSQL has a special numeric type for exact storage of numbers with up to 1000 digits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Moreover, in 2008 the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) published a draft technical report to extend the C programming language with fixed-point data types, for the benefit of programs running on embedded DSP processors.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Two main kinds of data types are proposed, _Fract (fractional part with a minimum 7-bit precision) and _Accum (_Fract with at least 4 bits of integer part).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) supports this draft.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Suppose there is the following multiplication with two fixed-point, 3-decimal-place numbers.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Note how, since there are 3 decimal places, we show the trailing zeros.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] To re-characterize this as an integer multiplication, we must first multiply by $1000\ (=10^{3})$ , moving all the decimal places into integer places, then we will multiply by $1/1000\ (=10^{-3})$ to put them back.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This works equivalently if we choose a different base, notably base 2 for computing, since a bit shift is the same as a multiplication or division by an order of 2.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Three decimal digits are equivalent to about 10 binary digits, so we should round 0.05 to 10 bits after the binary point.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] The closest approximation is then 0.0000110011.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This rounds to 11.023 with three digits after the decimal point.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Consider the task of computing the product of 1.2 and 5.6 with binary fixed point using 16 fraction bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] To represent the two numbers, one multiplies them by 216, obtaining 78 643.2 and 367 001.6; and round these values the nearest integers, obtaining 78 643 and 367 002.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] These numbers will fit comfortably into a 32-bit word with two's complement signed format.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Multiplying these integers together gives the 35-bit integer 28 862 138 286 with 32 fraction bits, without any rounding.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Note that storing this value directly into a 32-bit integer variable would result in overflow and loss of the most significant bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In practice, it would probably be stored in a signed 64-bit integer variable or register.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If the result is to be stored in the same format as the data, with 16 fraction bits, that integer should be divided by 216, which gives approximately 440 401.28, and then rounded to the nearest integer.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] This effect can be achieved by adding 215 and then shifting the result by 16 bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Taking into account the precision of the format, that value is better expressed as 6.719 986 ± 0.000 008 (not counting the error that comes from the operand approximations).
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] For a more complicated example, suppose that the two numbers 1.2 and 5.6 are represented in 32-bit fixed-point format with 30 and 20 fraction bits, respectively.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] If we choose to represent this value in signed 16-bit fixed format with 8 fraction bits, we must divide the integer product by 250−8 = 242 and round the result; which can be achieved by adding 241 and shifting by 42 bits.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] Various notations have been used to concisely specify the parameters of a fixed-point format.
[src:model-quantization/fixed-point-arithmetic] In the following list, *f* represents the number of fractional bits, *m* the number of magnitude or integer bits, *s* the number of sign bits (0/1 or some other alternative representation), and *b* the total number of bits.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Almost all modern uses follow the IEEE 754-2008 standard, where the 16-bit base-2 format is referred to as **binary16**, and the exponent uses 5 bits.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] This can express values in the range ±65,504, with the minimum value above 1 being 1 + 1/1024.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Several earlier 16-bit floating point formats have existed including that of Hitachi's HD61810 DSP of 1982 (a 4-bit exponent and a 12-bit mantissa), the top 16 bits of a 32-bit float (8 exponent and 7 mantissa bits) called a bfloat16, and Thomas J.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Scott's WIF of 1991 (5 exponent bits, 10 mantissa bits) and the 3dfx Voodoo Graphics processor of 1995 (same as Hitachi).
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] ILM was searching for an image format that could handle a wide dynamic range, but without the hard drive and memory cost of single or double precision floating point.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The hardware-accelerated programmable shading group led by John Airey at SGI (Silicon Graphics) used the s10e5 data type in 1997 as part of the "bali" design effort.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] This is described in a SIGGRAPH 2000 paper (see section 4.3) and further documented in US patent 7518615.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] It was popularized by its use in the open-source OpenEXR image format.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Nvidia and Microsoft defined the **half** datatype in the Cg language, released in early 2002, and implemented it in silicon in the GeForce FX, released in late 2002.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] However, hardware support for accelerated 16-bit floating point was later dropped by Nvidia before being reintroduced in the Tegra X1 mobile GPU in 2015.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The F16C extension in 2012 allows x86 processors to convert half-precision floats to and from single-precision floats with a machine instruction.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The format is assumed to have an implicit lead bit with value 1 unless the exponent field is stored with all zeros.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Thus, only 10 bits of the significand appear in the memory format but the total precision is 11 bits.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] In IEEE 754 parlance, there are 10 bits of significand, but there are 11 bits of significand precision (log10(211) ≈ 3.311 decimal digits, or 4 digits ± slightly less than 5 units in the last place).
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The half-precision binary floating-point exponent is encoded using an offset-binary representation, with the zero offset being 15; also known as exponent bias in the IEEE 754 standard.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Thus, as defined by the offset binary representation, in order to get the true exponent the offset of 15 has to be subtracted from the stored exponent.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The stored exponents 000002 and 111112 are interpreted specially.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The minimum strictly positive (subnormal) value is 2−24 ≈ 5.96 × 10−8.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The minimum positive normal value is 2−14 ≈ 6.10 × 10−5.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] These examples are given in bit representation of the floating-point value.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] This includes the sign bit, (biased) exponent, and significand.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] By default, 1/3 rounds down like for double precision, because of the odd number of bits in the significand.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The bits beyond the rounding point are 0101... which is less than 1/2 of a unit in the last place.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] ARM processors support (via a floating-point control register bit) an "alternative half-precision" format, which does away with the special case for an exponent value of 31 (111112).
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] It is almost identical to the IEEE format, but there is no encoding for infinity or NaNs; instead, an exponent of 31 encodes normalized numbers in the range 65536 to 131008.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Half precision is used in several computer graphics environments to store pixels, including MATLAB, OpenEXR, JPEG XR, GIMP, OpenGL, Vulkan, Cg, Direct3D, and D3DX.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The advantage over 8-bit or 16-bit integers is that the increased dynamic range allows for more detail to be preserved in highlights and shadows for images, and avoids gamma correction.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The advantage over 32-bit single-precision floating point is that it requires half the storage and bandwidth (at the expense of precision and range).
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Half precision can be useful for mesh quantization.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Mesh data is usually stored using 32-bit single-precision floats for the vertices, however in some situations it is acceptable to reduce the precision to only 16-bit half-precision, requiring only half the storage at the expense of some precision.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Mesh quantization can also be done with 8-bit or 16-bit fixed precision depending on the requirements.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Hardware and software for machine learning and neural networks often use half-precision arithmetic to accelerate computations.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] In these applications, the distinct bfloat16 format is sometimes preferred for its wider dynamic range than half-precision, and specialized floating point formats with only 8 bits or less are increasingly used to further accelerate certain computations.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] If the hardware has instructions to compute half-precision math, it is often faster than single or double precision, sometimes up to 4 times faster.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] In addition if the system has SIMD instructions, often one instruction can simultaneously operate on twice as many half values than float values.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Zig, Odin, and other languages provide support for half precisions with their `f16` type.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] .NET 5 introduced half precision floating point numbers with the `System.Half` standard library type.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] As of 16 July 2025, no .NET language (C#, F#, Visual Basic, and C++/CLI and C++/CX) has literals (e.g. in C#, `1.0f` has type `System.Single` or `1.0m` has type `System.Decimal`) or a keyword for the type.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Swift introduced half-precision floating point numbers in Swift 5.3 with the `Float16` type.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] OpenCL also supports half-precision floating point numbers with the half datatype on IEEE 754-2008 half-precision storage format.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] As of 31 May 2026, Rust is currently working on adding a new `f16` type for IEEE half-precision 16-bit floats.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Julia provides support for half-precision floating point numbers with the `Float16` type.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] C++ introduced half-precision since C++23 with the `std::float16_t` type.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Several versions of the ARM architecture have support for half precision.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Support for conversions with half-precision floats in the x86 instruction set is specified in the F16C instruction set extension, first introduced in 2009 by AMD and fairly broadly adopted by AMD and Intel CPUs by 2012.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] This was further extended up the AVX-512_FP16 instruction set extension implemented in the Intel Sapphire Rapids processor.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] On RISC-V, the `Zfh` and `Zfhmin` extensions provide hardware support for 16-bit half precision floats.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The `Zfhmin` extension is a minimal alternative to `Zfh`.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] On Power ISA, VSX and the not-yet-approved SVP64 extension provide hardware support for 16-bit half-precision floats as of PowerISA v3.1B and later.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Support for half precision on IBM Z is part of the Neural-network-processing-assist facility that IBM introduced with Telum.
[src:model-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] IBM refers to half precision floating point data as NNP-Data-Type 1 (16-bit).
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In the field of artificial intelligence, an **inference engine** is a software component of an intelligent system that applies logical rules to the knowledge base to deduce new information.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The first inference engines were components of expert systems.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The typical expert system consisted of a knowledge base and an inference engine.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The knowledge base stored facts about the world.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The inference engine applied logical rules to the knowledge base and deduced new knowledge.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] This process would iterate as each new fact in the knowledge base could trigger additional rules in the inference engine.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Inference engines work primarily in one of two modes either special rule or facts: forward chaining and backward chaining.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Forward chaining starts with the known facts and asserts new facts.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Backward chaining starts with goals, and works backward to determine what facts must be asserted so that the goals can be achieved.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Additionally, the concept of 'inference' has expanded to include the process through which trained neural networks generate predictions or decisions.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In this context, an 'inference engine' could refer to the specific part of the system, or even the hardware, that executes these operations.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] This type of inference plays a crucial role in various applications, including (but not limited to) image recognition, natural language processing, and autonomous vehicles.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The inference phase in these applications is typically characterized by a high volume of data inputs and real-time processing requirements.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The logic that an inference engine uses is typically represented as IF-THEN rules.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The general format of such rules is IF <logical expression> THEN <logical expression>.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Prior to the development of expert systems and inference engines, artificial intelligence researchers focused on more powerful theorem prover environments that offered much fuller implementations of first-order logic.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] For example, general statements that included universal quantification (for all X some statement is true) and existential quantification (there exists some X such that some statement is true).
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] What researchers discovered is that the power of these theorem-proving environments was also their drawback.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Back in 1965, it was far too easy to create logical expressions that could take an indeterminate or even infinite time to terminate.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] For example, it is common in universal quantification to make statements over an infinite set such as the set of all natural numbers.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Such statements are perfectly reasonable and even required in mathematical proofs but when included in an automated theorem prover executing on a computer may cause the computer to fall into an infinite loop.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Focusing on IF-THEN statements (what logicians call *modus ponens*) still gave developers a very powerful general mechanism to represent logic, but one that could be used efficiently with computational resources.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] What is more, there is some psychological research that indicates humans also tend to favor IF-THEN representations when storing complex knowledge.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] A simple example of *modus ponens* often used in introductory logic books is "If you are human then you are mortal".
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] A trivial example of how this rule would be used in an inference engine is as follows.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In *forward chaining*, the inference engine would find any facts in the knowledge base that matched Human(x) and for each fact it found would add the new information Mortal(x) to the knowledge base.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] So if it found an object called Socrates that was human it would deduce that Socrates was mortal.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In *backward chaining*, the system would be given a goal, e.g. answer the question is Socrates mortal?
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] It would search through the knowledge base and determine if Socrates was human and, if so, would assert he is also mortal.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] However, in backward chaining a common technique was to integrate the inference engine with a user interface.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In that way, rather than simply being automated the system could now be interactive.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In this trivial example, if the system was given the goal to answer the question if Socrates was mortal and it didn't yet know if he was human, it would generate a window to ask the user the question "Is Socrates human?" and would then use that information accordingly.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] This innovation of integrating the inference engine with a user interface led to the second early advancement of expert systems: explanation capabilities.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The explicit representation of knowledge as rules rather than code made it possible to generate explanations to users: both explanations in real time and after the fact.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] At first these explanations were not much different than the standard debugging information that developers deal with when debugging any system.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] However, an active area of research was utilizing natural language technology to ask, understand, and generate questions and explanations using natural languages rather than computer formalisms.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] An inference engine cycles through three sequential steps: *match rules*, *select rules*, and *execute rules*.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The execution of the rules will often result in new facts or goals being added to the knowledge base, which will trigger the cycle to repeat.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] This cycle continues until no new rules can be matched.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In the first step, *match rules*, the inference engine finds all of the rules that are triggered by the current contents of the knowledge base.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In forward chaining, the engine looks for rules where the antecedent (left hand side) matches some fact in the knowledge base.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In backward chaining, the engine looks for antecedents that can satisfy one of the current goals.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In the second step, *select rules*, the inference engine prioritizes the various rules that were matched to determine the order to execute them.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] In the final step, *execute rules*, the engine executes each matched rule in the order determined in step two and then iterates back to step one again.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The cycle continues until no new rules are matched.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Early inference engines focused primarily on forward chaining.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] These systems were usually implemented in the Lisp programming language.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Lisp was a frequent platform for early AI research due to its strong capability to do symbolic manipulation.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Also, as an interpreted language it offered productive development environments appropriate to debugging complex programs.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] A necessary consequence of these benefits was that Lisp programs tended to be slower and less robust than compiled languages of the time such as C.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] A common approach in these early days was to take an expert system application and repackage the inference engine used for that system as a re-usable tool other researchers could use for the development of other expert systems.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] For example, MYCIN was an early expert system for medical diagnosis and EMYCIN was an inference engine extrapolated from MYCIN and made available for other researchers.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] As expert systems moved from research prototypes to deployed systems there was more focus on issues such as speed and robustness.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] One of the first and most popular forward chaining engines was OPS5, which used the Rete algorithm to optimize the efficiency of rule firing.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Another very popular technology that was developed was the Prolog logic programming language.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] Prolog focused primarily on backward chaining and also featured various commercial versions and optimizations for efficiency and robustness.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] As expert systems prompted significant interest from the business world, various companies, many of them started or guided by prominent AI researchers created productized versions of inference engines.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] For example, Intellicorp was initially guided by Edward Feigenbaum.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] These inference engine products were also often developed in Lisp at first.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] However, demands for more affordable and commercially viable platforms eventually made personal computer platforms very popular.
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] ClipsRules and RefPerSys (inspired by CAIA and the work of Jacques Pitrat).
[src:model-quantization/inference-engine] The Frama-C static source code analyzer also uses some inference engine techniques.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Compressed models enable deployment on resource-constrained devices such as smartphones, embedded systems, edge computing devices, and consumer electronics computers.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Efficient inference is also valuable for large corporations that serve large model inference over an API, allowing them to reduce computational costs and improve response times for users.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Model compression is not to be confused with knowledge distillation, in which a smaller "student" model is *trained* to imitate the input-output behavior of a larger "teacher" model (as opposed to using the "teacher"'s trained parameters or the "teacher"'s training targets).
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Several techniques are employed for model compression.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Pruning sparsifies a large model by setting some parameters to exactly zero.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] This effectively reduces the number of parameters.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] This allows the use of sparse matrix operations, which are faster than dense matrix operations.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Pruning criteria can be based on magnitudes of parameters, the statistical pattern of neural activations, Hessian values, etc.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Quantization reduces the numerical precision of weights and activations.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] For example, instead of storing weights as 32-bit floating-point numbers, they can be represented using 8-bit integers.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Low-precision parameters take up less space, and takes less compute to perform arithmetic with.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] It is also possible to quantize some parameters more aggressively than others, so for example, a less important parameter can have 8-bit precision while another, more important parameter, can have 16-bit precision.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Inference with such models requires mixed-precision arithmetic.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Quantized models can also be used during training (rather than after training).
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] PyTorch implements automatic mixed-precision (AMP), which performs autocasting, gradient scaling, and loss scaling.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Weight matrices can be approximated by low-rank matrices.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Let W be a weight matrix of shape $m\times n$ .
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] A low-rank approximation is $W\approx UV^{T}$ , where U and V are matrices of shapes $m\times k,n\times k$ .
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] When k is small, this both reduces the number of parameters needed to represent W approximately, and accelerates matrix multiplication by W .
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Low-rank approximations can be found by singular value decomposition (SVD).
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] The choice of rank for each weight matrix is a hyperparameter, and jointly optimized as a mixed discrete-continuous optimization problem.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] The rank of weight matrices may also be pruned after training, taking into account the effect of activation functions like ReLU on the implicit rank of the weight matrices.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] Model compression may be decoupled from training, that is, a model is first trained without regard for how it might be compressed, then it is compressed.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] However, it may also be combined with training.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] The "train big, then compress" method trains a large model for a small number of training steps (less than it would be if it were trained to convergence), then heavily compress the model.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] It is found that at the same compute budget, this method results in a better model than lightly compressed, small models.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] In Deep Compression, the compression has three steps.
[src:model-quantization/model-compression] The SqueezeNet paper reported that Deep Compression achieved a compression ratio of 35 on AlexNet, and a ratio of ~10 on SqueezeNets.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In mathematics and digital signal processing, **quantization** is the process of mapping input values from a large set (often a continuous set) to output values in a (countable) smaller set, often with a finite number of elements.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Rounding and truncation are typical examples of quantization processes.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization is involved to some degree in nearly all digital signal processing, as the process of representing a signal in digital form ordinarily involves rounding.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization also forms the core of essentially all lossy compression algorithms.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The difference between an input value and its quantized value (such as round-off error) is referred to as **quantization error**, **noise** or **distortion**.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A device or algorithmic function that performs quantization is called a **quantizer**.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter is an example of a quantizer.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, rounding a real number x to the nearest integer value forms a very basic type of quantizer – a *uniform* one.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where the notation $\lfloor \ \rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] (The notation $\lceil \ \rceil$ denotes the ceiling function).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The essential property of a quantizer is having a countable set of possible output values smaller than the set of possible input values.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The members of the set of output values may have integer, rational, or real values.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For simple rounding to the nearest integer, the step size $\Delta$ is equal to 1.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] With $\Delta =1$ or with $\Delta$ equal to any other integer value, this quantizer has real-valued inputs and integer-valued outputs.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When the quantization step size (Δ) is small relative to the variation in the signal being quantized, it is relatively simple to show that the mean squared error produced by such a rounding operation will be approximately $\Delta ^{2}/12$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mean squared error is also called the quantization *noise power*.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Adding one bit to the quantizer halves the value of Δ, which reduces the noise power by the factor ⁠1/4⁠.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This two-stage decomposition applies equally well to vector as well as scalar quantizers.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Because quantization is a many-to-few mapping, it is an inherently non-linear and irreversible process (i.e., because the same output value is shared by multiple input values, it is impossible, in general, to recover the exact input value when given only the output value).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible input values may be infinitely large, and may possibly be continuous and therefore uncountable (such as the set of all real numbers, or all real numbers within some limited range).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible output values may be finite or countably infinite.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The input and output sets involved in quantization can be defined in a rather general way.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, vector quantization is the application of quantization to multi-dimensional (vector-valued) input data.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) can be modeled as two processes: sampling and quantization.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Sampling converts a time-varying voltage signal into a discrete-time signal, a sequence of real numbers.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization replaces each real number with an approximation from a finite set of discrete values.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Most commonly, these discrete values are represented as fixed-point words.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Though any number of quantization levels is possible, common word lengths are 8-bit (256 levels), 16-bit (65,536 levels) and 24-bit (16.8 million levels).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantizing a sequence of numbers produces a sequence of quantization errors, which is sometimes modeled as an additive random signal called **quantization noise** because of its stochastic behavior.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The more levels a quantizer uses, the lower is its quantization noise power.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Most uniform quantizers for signed input data can be classified as being of one of two types: *mid-riser* and *mid-tread*.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The terminology is based on what happens in the region around the value 0, and uses the analogy of viewing the input-output function of the quantizer as a stairway.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantizers have a zero-valued reconstruction level (corresponding to a *tread* of a stairway), while mid-riser quantizers have a zero-valued classification threshold (corresponding to a *riser* of a stairway).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantization involves rounding.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The formulas for mid-tread uniform quantization are provided in the previous section.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-riser quantization involves truncation.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Note that mid-riser uniform quantizers do not have a zero output value – their minimum output magnitude is half the step size.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In contrast, mid-tread quantizers do have a zero output level.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For some applications, having a zero output signal representation may be a necessity.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In general, a mid-riser or mid-tread quantizer may not actually be a *uniform* quantizer – i.e., the size of the quantizer's classification intervals may not all be the same, or the spacing between its possible output values may not all be the same.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The distinguishing characteristic of a mid-riser quantizer is that it has a classification threshold value that is exactly zero, and the distinguishing characteristic of a mid-tread quantizer is that is it has a reconstruction value that is exactly zero.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A **dead-zone quantizer** is a type of mid-tread quantizer with symmetric behavior around 0.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The region around the zero output value of such a quantizer is referred to as the *dead zone* or *deadband*.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The dead zone can sometimes serve the same purpose as a noise gate or squelch function.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Especially for compression applications, the dead-zone may be given a different width than that for the other steps.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where the function $\operatorname {sgn}$ ( ) is the sign function (also known as the *signum* function).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where $r_{k}$ is a reconstruction offset value in the range of 0 to 1 as a fraction of the step size.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Ordinarily, $0\leq r_{k}\leq {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ when quantizing input data with a typical probability density function (PDF) that is symmetric around zero and reaches its peak value at zero (such as a Gaussian, Laplacian, or generalized Gaussian PDF).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Although $r_{k}$ may depend on k in general and can be chosen to fulfill the optimality condition described below, it is often simply set to a constant, such as ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A very commonly used special case (e.g., the scheme typically used in financial accounting and elementary mathematics) is to set $w=\Delta$ and $r_{k}={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ for all k .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In this case, the dead-zone quantizer is also a uniform quantizer, since the central dead-zone of this quantizer has the same width as all of its other steps, and all of its reconstruction values are equally spaced as well.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A common assumption for the analysis of quantization error is that it affects a signal processing system in a similar manner to that of additive white noise – having negligible correlation with the signal and an approximately flat power spectral density.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The additive noise model is commonly used for the analysis of quantization error effects in digital filtering systems, and it can be very useful in such analysis.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It has been shown to be a valid model in cases of high-resolution quantization (small $\Delta$ relative to the signal strength) with smooth PDFs.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Additive noise behavior is not always a valid assumption.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization error (for quantizers defined as described here) is deterministically related to the signal and not entirely independent of it.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Thus, periodic signals can create periodic quantization noise.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] And in some cases, it can even cause limit cycles to appear in digital signal processing systems.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] One way to ensure effective independence of the quantization error from the source signal is to perform *dithered quantization* (sometimes with *noise shaping*), which involves adding random (or pseudo-random) noise to the signal prior to quantization.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In the typical case, the original signal is much larger than one least significant bit (LSB).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When this is the case, the quantization error is not significantly correlated with the signal and has an approximately uniform distribution.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When rounding is used to quantize, the quantization error has a mean of zero and the root mean square (RMS) value is the standard deviation of this distribution, given by $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {12}}}\mathrm {LSB} \ \approx \ 0.289\,\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When truncation is used, the error has a non-zero mean of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ and the RMS value is $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {3}}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Although rounding yields less RMS error than truncation, the difference is only due to the static (DC) term of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The RMS values of the AC error are exactly the same in both cases, so there is no special advantage of rounding over truncation in situations where the DC term of the error can be ignored (such as in AC-coupled systems).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In either case, the standard deviation, as a percentage of the full signal range, changes by a factor of 2 for each 1-bit change in the number of quantization bits.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The potential signal-to-quantization-noise power ratio therefore changes by 4, or $\scriptstyle 10\cdot \log _{10}(4)$ , approximately 6 dB per bit.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] At lower amplitudes, the quantization error becomes dependent on the input signal, resulting in distortion.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This distortion is created after the anti-aliasing filter, and if these distortions are above 1/2 the sample rate, they will alias back into the band of interest.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In order to make the quantization error independent of the input signal, the signal is dithered by adding noise to the signal.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This slightly reduces signal-to-noise ratio, but can completely eliminate the distortion.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization noise is a model of quantization error introduced by quantization in the ADC.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The noise is non-linear and signal-dependent.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It can be modeled in several different ways.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where Q is the number of quantization bits.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The most common test signals that fulfill this are full amplitude triangle waves and sawtooth waves.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio of 6.02 × 16 = 96.3 dB.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Here, the quantization noise is once again *assumed* to be uniformly distributed.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When the input signal has a high amplitude and a wide frequency spectrum, this is the case.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In this case a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-noise ratio of 98.09 dB.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The 1.761 difference in signal-to-noise only occurs due to the signal being a full-scale sine wave instead of a triangle or sawtooth.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For complex signals in high-resolution ADCs this is an accurate model.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For low-resolution ADCs, low-level signals in high-resolution ADCs, and for simple waveforms the quantization noise is not uniformly distributed, making this model inaccurate.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In these cases the quantization noise distribution is strongly affected by the exact amplitude of the signal.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The calculations are relative to full-scale input.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For smaller signals, the relative quantization distortion can be very large.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] To circumvent this issue, analog companding can be used, but this can introduce distortion.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Often, the design of a quantizer involves supporting only a limited range of possible output values and performing clipping to limit the output to this range whenever the input exceeds the supported range.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The error introduced by this clipping is referred to as *overload* distortion.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Within the extreme limits of the supported range, the amount of spacing between the selectable output values of a quantizer is referred to as its *granularity*, and the error introduced by this spacing is referred to as *granular* distortion.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It is common for the design of a quantizer to involve determining the proper balance between granular distortion and overload distortion.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For a given supported number of possible output values, reducing the average granular distortion may involve increasing the average overload distortion, and vice versa.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A technique for controlling the amplitude of the signal (or, equivalently, the quantization step size $\Delta$ ) to achieve the appropriate balance is the use of *automatic gain control* (AGC).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, in some quantizer designs, the concepts of granular error and overload error may not apply (e.g., for a quantizer with a limited range of input data or with a countably infinite set of selectable output values).
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] These two stages together comprise the mathematical operation of $y=Q(x)$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Entropy coding techniques can be applied to communicate the quantization indices from a source encoder that performs the classification stage to a decoder that performs the reconstruction stage.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] One way to do this is to associate each quantization index k with a binary codeword $c_{k}$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An important consideration is the number of bits used for each codeword, denoted here by $\mathrm {length} (c_{k})$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A key observation is that rate R depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the codeword lengths $\{\mathrm {length} (c_{k})\}_{k=1}^{M}$ , whereas the distortion D depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the reconstruction levels $\{y_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Solving the unconstrained problem is equivalent to finding a point on the convex hull of the family of solutions to an equivalent constrained formulation of the problem.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, finding a solution – especially a closed-form solution – to any of these three problem formulations can be difficult.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Solutions that do not require multi-dimensional iterative optimization techniques have been published for only three PDFs: the uniform, exponential, and Laplacian distributions.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Iterative optimization approaches can be used to find solutions in other cases.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This observation can be used to ease the analysis – given the set of $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ values, the value of each $y_{k}$ can be optimized separately to minimize its contribution to the distortion D .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The use of this approximation can allow the entropy coding design problem to be separated from the design of the quantizer itself.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Modern entropy coding techniques such as arithmetic coding can achieve bit rates that are very close to the true entropy of a source, given a set of known (or adaptively estimated) probabilities $\{p_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In some designs, rather than optimizing for a particular number of classification regions M , the quantizer design problem may include optimization of the value of M as well.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For some probabilistic source models, the best performance may be achieved when M approaches infinity.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The indices produced by an M -level quantizer can be coded using a fixed-length code using $R=\lceil \log _{2}M\rceil$ bits/symbol.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, when $M=$ 256 levels, the FLC bit rate R is 8 bits/symbol.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For this reason, such a quantizer has sometimes been called an 8-bit quantizer.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, using an FLC eliminates the compression improvement that can be obtained by use of better entropy coding.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Assuming an FLC with M levels, the rate–distortion minimization problem can be reduced to distortion minimization alone.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] which places each reconstruction value at the centroid (conditional expected value) of its associated classification interval.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Lloyd's Method I algorithm, originally described in 1957, can be generalized in a straightforward way for application to vector data.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This generalization results in the Linde–Buzo–Gray (LBG) or k-means classifier optimization methods.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the technique can be further generalized in a straightforward way to also include an entropy constraint for vector data.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The Lloyd–Max quantizer is actually a uniform quantizer when the input PDF is uniformly distributed over the range $[y_{1}-\Delta /2,~y_{M}+\Delta /2)$ .
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, for a source that does not have a uniform distribution, the minimum-distortion quantizer may not be a uniform quantizer.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The property of 6 dB improvement in SQNR for each extra bit used in quantization is a well-known figure of merit.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, it must be used with care: this derivation is only for a uniform quantizer applied to a uniform source.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For other source PDFs and other quantizer designs, the SQNR may be somewhat different from that predicted by 6 dB/bit, depending on the type of PDF, the type of source, the type of quantizer, and the bit rate range of operation.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, it is common to assume that for many sources, the slope of a quantizer SQNR function can be approximated as 6 dB/bit when operating at a sufficiently high bit rate.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] At asymptotically high bit rates, the 6 dB/bit approximation is supported for many source PDFs by rigorous theoretical analysis.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the structure of the optimal scalar quantizer (in the rate–distortion sense) approaches that of a uniform quantizer under these conditions.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Many physical quantities are actually quantized by physical entities.
[src:model-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Examples of fields where this limitation applies include electronics (due to electrons), optics (due to photons), biology (due to DNA), physics (due to Planck limits) and chemistry (due to molecules).
